5. Object and Reference Variables

This is one of the most important topics in OOP.

When we create an object:

p1 = Point(3, 4)

Many students think p1 directly stores the object.

But actually:

p1 stores the reference/address of the object.

So p1 is called a reference variable.

Simple Example
class Person:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

p1 = Person("Vansh")

Here, the object is created in memory, and p1 points to that object.

Think of it like:

p1  --->  Person object
6. Multiple Reference Variables

One object can have many reference variables.

Example:

class Person:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

p1 = Person("Vansh")
p2 = p1

print(p1.name)
print(p2.name)

Output:

Vansh
Vansh

Now both p1 and p2 are pointing to the same object.

p1  ----\
         ---> Person object
p2  ----/

Now if we change using p2:

p2.name = "Viraj"

Then:

print(p1.name)

Output:

Viraj

Because both variables are pointing to the same object.

7. Passing Object to Function

When we pass an object to a function, the reference is passed.

Example:

class Person:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

def change_name(person):
    person.name = "Rahul"

p1 = Person("Vansh")

change_name(p1)

print(p1.name)

Output:

Rahul
Why?

Because person inside the function and p1 outside the function are pointing to the same object.

So changing the object inside the function also affects the original object.

8. Mutability of Objects

Most user-defined objects in Python are mutable.

Mutable means:

The object can be changed after creation.

Example:

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

s1 = Student("Aman")
s1.name = "Rohan"

print(s1.name)

Output:

Rohan

The object was changed after creation, so it is mutable.

9. Encapsulation

Encapsulation means:

Binding data and methods together inside a class and hiding important data from direct outside access.

In simple words:

Encapsulation protects the internal data of an object.

Real-Life Example

Think of an ATM machine.

You can:

Withdraw money
Check balance
Change PIN

But you cannot directly open the ATM machine and change the bank database.

That is encapsulation.

The ATM gives you controlled access.

Similarly, in Python classes, we should not allow direct access to important data.

10. Why Encapsulation is Needed?

Suppose we have a bank account class:

class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, balance):
        self.balance = balance

Now anyone can do:

account = BankAccount(10000)
account.balance = -50000

This is dangerous.

A bank balance should not become negative directly.

So we protect the data.

11. Private Attributes

In Python, we can make an attribute private using double underscore __.

Example:

class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, balance):
        self.__balance = balance

Now __balance becomes private.

It cannot be accessed directly from outside the class.

Example:

account = BankAccount(10000)
print(account.__balance)

This will give an error.

12. Getter Method

A getter method is used to safely read private data.

Example:

class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, balance):
        self.__balance = balance

    def get_balance(self):
        return self.__balance

Usage:

account = BankAccount(10000)
print(account.get_balance())

Output:

10000
13. Setter Method

A setter method is used to safely update private data.

Example:

class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, balance):
        self.__balance = balance

    def get_balance(self):
        return self.__balance

    def set_balance(self, amount):
        if amount >= 0:
            self.__balance = amount
        else:
            print("Balance cannot be negative")

Usage:

account = BankAccount(10000)

account.set_balance(20000)
print(account.get_balance())

account.set_balance(-5000)

Output:

20000
Balance cannot be negative
14. Encapsulation Full Example
class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, name, balance):
        self.name = name
        self.__balance = balance

    def get_balance(self):
        return self.__balance

    def deposit(self, amount):
        if amount > 0:
            self.__balance += amount
            print("Money deposited successfully")
        else:
            print("Invalid deposit amount")

    def withdraw(self, amount):
        if amount <= self.__balance:
            self.__balance -= amount
            print("Withdrawal successful")
        else:
            print("Insufficient balance")

Usage:

account = BankAccount("Vansh", 10000)

account.deposit(5000)
print(account.get_balance())

account.withdraw(3000)
print(account.get_balance())

Output:

Money deposited successfully
15000
Withdrawal successful
12000
15. Important Point About Private Variables

Python does not make private variables completely private.

It performs something called name mangling.

Example:

self.__balance

internally becomes something like:

_BankAccount__balance

So technically it can still be accessed, but we should not do that.

Example:

print(account._BankAccount__balance)

This may work, but it is a bad practice.

16. Instance Variables

Instance variables are variables that are different for every object.

Example:

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name, marks):
        self.name = name
        self.marks = marks

Here:

self.name
self.marks

are instance variables.

Example:

s1 = Student("Aman", 90)
s2 = Student("Rohan", 80)

Here:

s1.name = "Aman"
s2.name = "Rohan"

Both objects have their own separate values.

17. Static Variables

Static variables are shared by all objects of a class.

They belong to the class, not to a particular object.

Example:

class Student:
    school_name = "ABC School"

    def __init__(self, name, marks):
        self.name = name
        self.marks = marks

Here:

school_name

is a static variable.

It is common for all students.

Example
class Student:
    school_name = "ABC School"

    def __init__(self, name, marks):
        self.name = name
        self.marks = marks

s1 = Student("Aman", 90)
s2 = Student("Rohan", 80)

print(s1.school_name)
print(s2.school_name)
print(Student.school_name)

Output:

ABC School
ABC School
ABC School
18. Instance Variable vs Static Variable
Basis	Instance Variable	Static Variable
Belongs to	Object	Class
Value	Different for each object	Same for all objects
Created inside	Constructor using self	Directly inside class
Accessed using	Object name	Class name
Example	self.name	school_name
19. Why Static Variables Are Useful?

Static variables are useful when some data is common for all objects.

Example:

class Employee:
    company_name = "Google"

    def __init__(self, name, salary):
        self.name = name
        self.salary = salary

Here, every employee may have different name and salary, but the company name is same.

So company_name should be static.

20. Static Methods

Static methods are methods that do not need object data.

They are utility/helper methods inside a class.

To create a static method, we use:

@staticmethod

Example:

class Math:
    @staticmethod
    def add(a, b):
        return a + b

Usage:

print(Math.add(10, 20))

Output:

30
21. Important Point About Static Method

A static method does not use:

self

Because it does not depend on object data.

Example:

class Student:
    school_name = "ABC School"

    def __init__(self, name, marks):
        self.name = name
        self.marks = marks

    @staticmethod
    def welcome_message():
        print("Welcome to Student Management System")

Usage:

Student.welcome_message()

Output:

Welcome to Student Management System
22. Instance Method vs Static Method
Basis	Instance Method	Static Method
Uses self?	Yes	No
Belongs to	Object	Class
Access object data?	Yes	No
Decorator needed?	No	@staticmethod
Example	get_marks(self)	welcome_message()
23. Full Example: Student Class
class Student:
    school_name = "ABC School"

    def __init__(self, name, marks):
        self.name = name
        self.__marks = marks

    def get_marks(self):
        return self.__marks

    def set_marks(self, marks):
        if 0 <= marks <= 100:
            self.__marks = marks
        else:
